<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="93" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[111,648,1160,1421]" pageId="10" pageNumber="93">
DIAGNOSIS. — This new genus shares one important character with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vidal" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[252,311,1187,1210]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Fulvia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Capnodiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="93" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[252,311,1187,1210]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="93">Fulvia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: stronger ribs on the posterior slope than on the median and anterior shell regions (
<bibRefCitation author="VIDAL J." pageId="10" pageNumber="93" pagination="93 - 118" refId="ref18357" refString="VIDAL J. 1994. - A review of the genus Fulvia Gray, 1853 (Mollusca, Bivalvia). Apex 9 (4): 93 - 118." type="journal article" year="1994">Vidal 1994</bibRefCitation>
). However, it differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vidal" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[415,475,1240,1263]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Fulvia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Capnodiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="93" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[415,475,1240,1263]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="93">Fulvia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having: 1) very asymmetrical or “fragiform” outline, with a relatively pronounced keel or carina delimiting the posterior shell region (a character also shown by 
<taxonomicName authority="Vidal, 1994" authorityName="Vidal" authorityYear="1994" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" genus="Fulvia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Capnodiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="93" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="fragiformis">
<emphasis box="[424,584,1319,1342]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="93">Fulvia fragiformis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="VIDAL J." pageId="10" pageNumber="93" pagination="93 - 118" refId="ref18357" refString="VIDAL J. 1994. - A review of the genus Fulvia Gray, 1853 (Mollusca, Bivalvia). Apex 9 (4): 93 - 118." type="journal article" year="1994">Vidal, 1994</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
); 2) posterior ribs and interstices that are very strong and triangular; 3) poorly developed anterior ribbing; and 4) no ocular organs on the siphonal tentacles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="93" type="materials_examined">
